  "topic_name": "Matter and Materials",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Everything around us is made of matter. Matter exists in three states: solids, liquids, and gases. Solids have fixed shape and size. Liquids take the shape of their container and can flow. Gases fill up the entire space and can be compressed. Matter can change from one state to another through heating or cooling.",
    "rules": [
      "Solids have fixed shape and size (example: stone, ice)",
      "Liquids take the shape of their container and can flow (example: water, milk)",
      "Gases have no fixed shape or size and fill entire space (example: air)",
      "Melting: solid to liquid (ice to water)",
      "Freezing: liquid to solid (water to ice)",
      "Evaporation: liquid to gas (water to steam)"
    ]
  },
